  heroSubtitle="Vital Records"
  heroIntro={`Birth certificates establish your child's identity and your legal relationship to them. For dependent visas, school enrollment, and official UAE records, you need certified Arabic translation that authorities accept without question. We translate birth certificates from every country, in every language, with the precision that government systems demand.

In the UAE's administrative framework, a birth certificate is far more than a record of when and where your child was born. It is the foundational document that establishes your legal relationship to your child in the eyes of UAE authorities. When you apply for a dependent visa, GDRFA uses the translated birth certificate to confirm that the child you are sponsoring is actually your child. When you enroll in a KHDA school, the administration needs to see official documentation of your child's age and identity. When you add your child to your Emirates ID family book, the birth certificate provides the legal basis.

The most common issue with birth certificate translation is name consistency. UAE government systems—GDRFA, ICP, MOHRE, and others—match names character by character. If your child's birth certificate shows "Mohammad" but their passport shows "Mohammed," the system will flag a mismatch. If your name appears as "Arun Kumar" on the birth certificate but "Arunkumar" on your passport, that creates a discrepancy. We check these details before translation begins and advise you on how to handle any variations. Sometimes a simple statutory declaration at your embassy resolves it. Sometimes you need additional documentation.

Birth certificates come in many formats depending on the issuing country. Some countries issue short-form certificates (computerized extracts showing basic information) and long-form certificates (full registration details with additional information). Hospital birth records may be separate from official registration certificates. Delayed registration certificates, issued when births are registered after the normal filing period, have their own specific formats and may include court orders. We handle all these variations.

For <a href="/services/attestation/">attestation</a> requirements, the chain depends on your home country. Generally, foreign birth certificates need home country authentication (Ministry of Foreign Affairs or equivalent), UAE Embassy attestation, and UAE MOFA attestation before they have full legal effect in the UAE. Some countries that are members of the <a href="/services/attestation/apostille/">Hague Apostille Convention</a> follow a slightly different process. We advise on the specific requirements for your situation.

Beyond dependent visas, translated birth certificates are needed for school enrollment at KHDA-regulated institutions, adding children to health insurance policies, Emirates ID applications for children, passport renewals at your embassy, opening bank accounts for minors, and establishing inheritance rights. Each use may have slightly different requirements—school enrollment may not always require attestation, while court submissions definitely do.

We translate birth certificates from India, Pakistan, Philippines, UK, USA, Canada, Australia, European countries, Arab countries, and elsewhere. Languages we commonly translate include Hindi, Urdu, Tagalog, Arabic, French, German, Spanish, Russian, Chinese, and many others. The translation captures every detail on the certificate: child's name, date and time of birth, place of birth, registration number, parent names, and any additional information the certificate contains.

Standard birth certificate translation completes within 2-4 hours. Express same-day service is available when you have urgent visa appointments or school deadlines. For families sponsoring multiple children, we offer package pricing for translating several certificates together.`}
